  "topic_name": "Magnetism",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "A magnetic field is a region where magnetic forces act. Magnetic field lines show the direction and strength of the field. Current-carrying conductors produce magnetic fields (Oersted's experiment). The right-hand thumb rule gives the field direction around a straight conductor. Electromagnets are temporary magnets made by passing current through a coil around a soft iron core. A current-carrying conductor in a magnetic field experiences a force (Fleming's left-hand rule). The DC motor converts electrical energy to mechanical energy using this principle.",
    "rules": [
      "Magnetic field lines: N to S outside, never cross, denser = stronger",
      "Right-hand thumb rule: thumb = current, curled fingers = field direction",
      "Electromagnet strength depends on: current, turns, core material",
      "Fleming's left-hand rule: First finger = Field, seCond finger = Current, thuMb = Motion",
      "DC motor: armature, commutator, brushes, field magnets"
    ]
  },
